 ''[[Private Eyes (TV series)|Private Eyes]]''\n| Robyn Westing (1 episode)\n|-\n| 2016 \n| ''[[Wynonna Earp (TV series)|Wynonna Earp]]''\n| Hetty Tate (1 episode)\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''The Perfect Soulmate'' (TV Movie)<ref name=\"soulmate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.themoviescene.co.uk/reviews/the-perfect-soulmate-2017/the-perfect-soulmate-2017.html |title= The Perfect Soulmate |publisher= themoviescene.co.uk | year=2017 }}</ref>\n| Sarah Miles\n|-\n| 2009\u201317 \n| ''[[Murdoch Mysteries]]'' (TV Series) <ref name=\"cbs1\" />\n| Winifred Pink / Winifred 'Freddie' Pink / Lillie Dunn (5 episodes)\n|-\n| 2018\u201319\n| ''[[Pure (Canadian TV series)|Pure]]'' <ref name=\"nov\">{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/television/karine-vanasse-relishes-her-return-to-ctvs-real-and-raw-cardinal |title= A conversation with Alex Paxton-Beesley of CBC's \"Pure\" |publisher= Novella Magazine | year=2017 }}</ref>\n| Anna Funk (12 episodes)\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Impulse (TV series)|Impulse]]''\n| Sabine (3 episodes) \n|-\n| 2018 \n| ''[[Cardinal (TV series)|Cardinal]]'' <ref name=\"eh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tv-eh.com/tag/alex-paxton-beesley/ |title= Tag archives -Alex Paxton-Beesley |publisher= tv-eh.com |year=2018 }}</ref>\n| Red (6 episodes) <ref name=\"red\">{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/television/karine-vanasse-relishes-her-return-to-ctvs-real-and-raw-cardinal |title= Karine Vanasse relishes her return to CTV's 'real and raw' Cardinal |publisher= montrealgazette.com | year=2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020 \n| ''[[The Bold Type ]]'' <ref name=\"bold\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lindamaleh/2020/03/27/review-the-bold-type-season-4-spring-finale-makes-bold-moves/#a0c24726af13|title= Review: \u2018The Bold Type\u2019 Season 4 Spring Finale Makes Bold Moves |publisher= forbes.com/| year=2020}}</ref>\n| Ava Rose (1 episode - Some kind of wonderful)\n|}\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|nm1705735}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paxton-Beesley, Alex}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Canadian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Canadian television actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Grammarspellchecker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTV and film", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alex_Paxton-Beesley"}
{"title_page": "Nathaniel Levi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n|name = Nathaniel Levi\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1830|01|20|df=yes}}<ref name = adb>{{cite AuDB |first= L. E.|last= Fredman|authorlink= |title= Levi, Nathaniel (1830\u20131908)|volume= |edition= |year= 1974|id2= levi-nathaniel-4015/text6365|accessdate= 13 April 2017}}</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Liverpool]], Lancashire, England<ref name = adb/>\n|death_date = {{death date and age|1908|09|11|1830|01|20|df=yes}}<ref name = obit_Age>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article202173488 |title=ABOUT PEOPLE. |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=16693 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=12 September 1908 |accessdate=13 April 2017 |page=13 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n|death_place = [[St Kilda, Victoria]], Australia<ref name = obit_Age/>\n|spouse = Sarah nee Levy<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article154868370 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=349 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=30 November 1855 |accessdate=16 April 2017 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> \n|occupation = auctioneer, company director, distiller, politician\n|module = {{infobox officeholder |embed = yes\n|office = [[Legislative Assembly of Victoria]] representative for [[Electoral district of Maryborough (Victoria)|Maryborough]]\n|term = 1860\u20131865\n|office2 = [[Legislative Assembly of Victoria]] representative for [[Electoral district of East Melbourne|East Melbourne]]\n|term2 = 1866\u20131868\n|office3 = [[Legislative Council of Victoria]] representative for [[North Yarra Province]]\n|term3 = 1892\u20131904\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Nathaniel Levi''' (1830\u20131908) was a [[Liverpool]] born [[Victoria, Australia|Victorian]] politician and businessman.\n\nHe arrived at [[Hobson's Bay]] in April 1854 in the ''Matilda Wattenbach''.<ref name = adb/>\n\nLevi was prominent in the Jewish community, president of the Melbourne Hebrew Congregation in 1880\u201382 and 1904\u201305.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n.\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levi, Nathaniel}}\n[[Category:1830 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian people of English-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to colonial Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Council]]\n\n\n{{Australia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n|name = Nathaniel Levi\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1830|01|20|df=yes}}<ref name = adb>{{cite AuDB |first= L. E.|last= Fredman|authorlink= |title= Levi, Nathaniel (1830\u20131908)|volume= |edition= |year= 1974|id2= levi-nathaniel-4015/text6365|accessdate= 13 April 2017}}</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Liverpool]], Lancashire, England<ref name = adb/>\n|death_date = {{death date and age|1908|09|11|1830|01|20|df=yes}}<ref name = obit_Age>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article202173488 |title=ABOUT PEOPLE. |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=16693 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=12 September 1908 |accessdate=13 April 2017 |page=13 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n|death_place = [[St Kilda, Victoria]], Australia<ref name = obit_Age/>\n|spouse = Sarah nee Levy<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article154868370 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=349 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=30 November 1855 |accessdate=16 April 2017 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> \n|occupation = auctioneer, company director, distiller, politician\n|module = {{infobox officeholder |embed = yes\n|office = [[Legislative Assembly of Victoria]] representative for [[Electoral district of Maryborough (Victoria)|Maryborough]]\n|term = 1860-1865\n|office2 = [[Legislative Assembly of Victoria]] representative for [[Electoral district of East Melbourne|East Melbourne]]\n|term2 = 1866-1868\n|office3 = [[Legislative Council of Victoria]] representative for [[North Yarra Province]]\n|term3 = 1892-1904\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Nathaniel Levi''' (1830-1908) was a [[Liverpool]] born [[Victoria, Australia|Victorian]] politician and businessman.\n\nHe arrived at [[Hobson's Bay]] in April 1854 in the ''Matilda Wattenbach''.<ref name = adb/>\n\nLevi was prominent in the Jewish community, president of the Melbourne Hebrew Congregation in 1880-82 and 1904\u201305.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n.\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levi, Nathaniel}}\n[[Category:1830 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian people of English-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to colonial Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Council]]\n\n\n{{Australia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nathaniel_Levi"}
{"title_page": "Aleksandr Kerzhakov", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Eastern Slavic name|Anatolyevich|Kerzhakov}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Aleksandr Kerzhakov\n| image       = Kerzhakov11.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Aleksandr Kerzhakov in 2017\n| fullname    = Aleksandr Anatolyevich Kerzhakov\n| height      = 1.76m\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1982|11|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Kingisepp]], [[Russian SFSR]]\n| currentclub = [[Russia national under-18 football team|Russia U18]] (manager)\n| clubnumber  = \n| position    = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| years1 = 2001\u20132006 | clubs1 = [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]] | caps1  = 156 | goals1 = 64\n| years2 = 2006\u20132008 | clubs2 = [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]                               | caps2  =  26 | goals2 =  8\n| years3 = 2008\u20132010 | clubs3 = [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]]                   | caps3  =  51 | goals3 = 19\n| years4 = 2010\u20132017 | clubs4 = [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]] | caps4  = 129 | goals4 = 56 \n| years5 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[FC Z\u00fcrich|Z\u00fcrich]] (loan)                        | caps5  =  17 | goals5 =  5\n| totalcaps = 379 | totalgoals = 152\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132016 | nationalteam1  = [[Russia national football team|Russia]] | nationalcaps1  = 91 | nationalgoals1 = 30\n| manageryears1 = 2017\u20132018 | managerclubs1 = [[Russia national under-17 football team|Russia U17]]\n| manageryears2 = 2018\u2013     | managerclubs2 = [[Russia national under-18 football team|Russia U18]]\n}}\n\n'''Aleksandr Anatolyevich Kerzhakov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432}} {{IPA-ru|\u0250l\u02b2\u026a\u02c8ksandr \u0250n\u0250\u02c8tol\u02b2\u026av\u02b2\u026at\u0255 k\u02b2\u026ar\u0290\u0250\u02c8kof|}}; born 27 November 1982) is a Russian [[Association football|football]] manager and a former [[Russia national football team|Russian international]] striker. He is the manager of the [[Russia national under-18 football team]].\n\nHe is the most prolific goalscorer in the history of Russian football, with the number of goals scored in competitive games standing at 233. He is described as a forward who likes to \"drop deep to link with the midfield, expecting players to break beyond him\" for whom he creates space.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Jonathan|title=Euro 2012: Russia|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/writers/jonathan_wilson/05/29/euro.2012.russia.preview/index.html|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=2 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nA full international since 2002, Kerzhakov has earned 90 [[Cap (association football)|caps]] for Russia and played at two [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]]s and two [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]]s. In 2014, he surpassed the record held by [[Vladimir Beschastnykh]] for most goals for Russia.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Zenit===\nBorn in [[Kingisepp]], [[Leningrad Oblast]], he spent the 2000 season at amateur club [[FC Svetogorets Svetogorsk]], helping them win the Northwest regional league by scoring 18 goals.\n\nIn 2001 Kerzhakov transferred to [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg]], debuting in March and scoring his first goal in June against [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]]. In his first season, Kerzhakov was the second choice striker behind [[Hennadiy Popovych]]. However, later in 2001, he helped Zenit finish third in the [[Russian Premier League]] and runners-up in 2003. In 2002, Kerzhakov quickly developed a striking partnership with [[Andrei Arshavin]] which earned them both call-ups to the [[Russia national football team|Russian national team]]. That year Kerzhakov went to represent Russia at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].\n\nIn 2003, Czech manager [[Vlastimil Petr\u017eela]] promoted Kerzhakov as first choice striker and he became the top scorer of the Russian Premier League in 2004. While under Petr\u017eela, Kerzhakov was given a starting position in all four group games of the [[UEFA Cup 2004-05|2004\u201305 UEFA Cup]] and went on to score a hat trick in a 5\u20131 victory over [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]. The following season, he was in the starting line up once again in Zenit's second straight [[UEFA Cup 2005-06|UEFA Cup]] campaign. Zenit qualified for the round of 32 by overcoming [[Vit\u00f3ria SC|Vit\u00f3ria]], [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]], [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton]], and [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]. In the knockout stages, Kerzhakov scored against [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]] and [[Olympique de Marseille]] as Zenit reached the quarterfinals to face Sevilla.<ref name=\"fc-zenit1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fc-zenit.ru/info/personInfo.phtml?id=6 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100120074316/http://www.fc-zenit.ru/info/personInfo.phtml?id=6 |archivedate=20 January 2010 }}</ref> Kerzhakov gave his best performance by scoring a goal in the away leg but could not save his team as they lost out 5\u20132 on aggregate.\n\nThe appointment of [[Dick Advocaat]] in 2006 resulted in a drastic drop of appearances after being demoted to the bench. Kerzhakov decided to leave Zenit after his relationship with Advocaat deteriorated.<ref name=\"Sevilla move for Kerzhakov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/news/kind=1/newsid=493534.html |title=Sevilla move for Kerzhakov |date=28 December 2006 |accessdate=2 March 2008 |publisher=UEFA.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080229154202/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/news/kind%3D1/newsid%3D493534.html |archivedate=29 February 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Sevilla===\nOn 28 December 2006, Kerzhakov transferred to [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], signing a five-and-a-half-year contract worth \u20ac5&nbsp;million, as part of the deal of the partnership of the clubs.<ref name=\"Sevilla move for Kerzhakov\"/> Under then manager [[Juande Ramos]], Kerzhakov was third choice striker behind [[Lu\u00eds Fabiano]] and [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Kanout\u00e9]]. He played his first match on 14 January 2007 and scored his first goal on 28 January 2007 in a 4\u20132 victory against [[Levante UD]]. He scored the winning goal against Tottenham in a 4\u20133 victory in the UEFA Cup quarter-finals on 5 April 2007. Kerzhakov later contributed to Sevilla's victorious run in the 2006\u201307 UEFA Cup season.\n\nAfter Juande Ramos resigned at Sevilla to manage [[Tottenham Hotspur]] in October 2007, Kerzhakov's playing time decreased under caretaker manager [[Manuel Jim\u00e9nez Jim\u00e9nez|Manuel Jim\u00e9nez]]. He made only four appearances, being the fifth striker behind [[Lu\u00eds Fabiano]], [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Kanout\u00e9]], [[Javier Chevant\u00f3n]], and [[Arouna Kon\u00e9]]. It was speculated that Kerzhakov would quit Sevilla following interest from Tottenham, [[Manchester United]], and [[Paris Saint-Germain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/spurs-tracking-sevilla-striker-kerzhakov-162061#.USHDZaV4K9c|title=Spurs tracking Sevilla striker Kerzhakov|date=27 December 2007|accessdate=18 February 2013|publisher=Tribal Football/}}</ref> However, according to Russian newspaper ''[[Sport-Express]]'', on 30 January 2008, Kerzhakov stated he would stay at Sevilla to help in the [[La Liga]] and [[UEFA Champions League]] campaigns.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://english.sport-express.ru/news/13_1707/ \n |title=Kerzhakov Stays in Sevilla \n |accessdate=6 February 2008 \n |date=30 January 2008 \n |publisher=Sport Express Daily \n |work=english.sport-express.ru/ \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719085353/http://english.sport-express.ru/news/13_1707/ \n |archivedate=19 July 2011 \n}}</ref>\n\n===Dynamo Moscow===\n[[Image:Dinamo-Celtic (2).jpg|upright|thumb|Kerzhakov in action for Dynamo Moscow in 2009]]\nIn February 2008, after being left out of Sevilla's Champions League tie against [[Fenerbah\u00e7e]], Kerzhakov signed a three-year contract with Russian side [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dinamo Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=663861.html |title=Dinamo bring Sevilla's Kerzhakov home |date=25 February 2008 |accessdate=2 March 2008 |publisher=UEFA.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080228195739/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind%3D1/newsid%3D663861.html |archivedate=28 February 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Kerzhakov quickly established himself as a first choice striker with [[Tsvetan Genkov]] and [[C\u00edcero Semedo|C\u00edcero]]. He scored his first goal for Dynamo with a powerful strike from outside of the penalty area against [[FC Moscow]]. During the [[2008 Russian Premier League|2008 season]] Kerzhakov become the top scorer in the squad as Dynamo finished third to earn a play off spot in the qualifiers for the UEFA Champions League.\n\nDuring the 2009 season Kerzhakov maintained his spot as a first choice striker ahead of [[Aleksandr Kokorin]] and [[Fedor Smolov]] but the season turned out to be less successful as Dynamo finished eighth and lost to Celtic and CSKA Sophia in an attempt to qualify for the [[2009-10 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and [[2009-10 UEFA Europa League|inaugural Europa League]].\n\n===Return to Zenit===\nIn January 2010, Kerzhakov rescinded the last year of his contract with Dynamo and returned to his first professional club [[Zenit St. Petersburg]],.<ref name=\"fc-zenit1\"/> Under incoming manager Luciano Spalletti, Kerzhakov was designated the first choice striker and managed twenty six appearances. He scored his first goal against CSKA Moscow in April of that year and followed this up with two hat tricks against [[R.S.C. Anderlecht]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]] and [[FC Saturn Moscow Region|Saturn Moscow]] in the [[2010 Russian Premier League|domestic league]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/matches/season=2011/round=2000128/match=2002925/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Kerzhakov class leaves Anderlecht reeling |publisher=UEFA.com |author=Chris Burke |date=16 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918062337/http://www1.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/matches/season%3D2011/round%3D2000128/match%3D2002925/postmatch/report/index.html |archivedate=18 September 2010  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sports.ru/football/73241243.html|title=\u041a\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0438\u043b \u0434\u0432\u0430 \u0445\u0435\u0442-\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0432 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0430\u0445|publisher=sports.ru|date=25 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe following season began with a disappointing loss to FC Twente in the Europa League round of 16. However, Kerzhakov went on to have a stellar season netting 23 goals in 32 appearances in the Russian Premier League. Zenit finished first in the regular season and then won the [[2011\u201312 Russian Premier League#Second phase|championship group]] in the spring of 2012 to claim their second league title in two years.\n\nKerzhakov officially retired on 13 July 2017 and was appointed the coordinator of Zenit's youth and academy teams.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg]]|url=http://fc-zenit.ru/news/2017-07-13-aleksandr-kerzhakov-naznachen-dolzhnost-koordinatora-komand-akademii.htm|script-title=ru:\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041a\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043a\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434 \u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0438|date=13 July 2017|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Aleksandr Kerzhakov 2011 Russia.jpg|thumb|upright|Kerzhakov with the Russia national football team in 2011]]\n\n===Early international career===\nKerzhakov began playing for the [[Russia national under-21 football team|Russian U21]] team in 2001. He made his senior debut for [[Russia national football team|Russia]] in a friendly against [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] on 27 March 2002. Two months later, he was selected by [[Oleg Romantsev]] for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]. He was on the bench for Russia's first two games against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] and [[Japan national football team|Japan]], but came on for [[Valery Karpin]] against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] in the 82nd minute of the last group game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Belgium - Russia|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/worldcup/koreajapan2002/matches/round=43950100/match=43950046/index.html|publisher=[[FIFA]]|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref> Russia lost the match 3&ndash;2 and were eliminated.\n\nIn 2003, became the winner of [[Cyprus International Football Tournaments]], played in the final match<ref>http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cypr-intltourn03.html</ref>\nAfter Romanstev's sacking, new manager [[Valery Gazzaev]] made Kerzhakov a regular call up in the squad. Just prior to the start of the [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualification|UEFA Euro 2004 qualifiers]], Kerzhakov scored his first goal for Russia in a friendly 1\u20131 draw against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] on 21 August 2002. Despite making eight appearances in the qualification tournament, for the [[UEFA Euro 2004|final tournament]] he was selected by [[Georgi Yartsev]] as one of four strikers in the squad behind with [[Dmitri Bulykin]], [[Dmitri Kirichenko]], and [[Dmitri Sychev]]. He was on the bench for Russia's games against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and [[Greece national football team|Greece]], but played a full game against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].\n\n===2004\u20132010===\nAfter Euro 2004, Yartsev continued to pick Kerzhakov as a substitute for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2006 World Cup qualifiers]]. Russia started strongly but after a 7\u20131 loss to Portugal and a 1\u20131 draw with Estonia, Yartsev resigned. Yartsev's successor [[Yuri Semin]], promoted Kerzhakov to the starting position after Bulykin and Kirichenko were dropped from the squad. Along with the recall of his then clubmate [[Andrei Arshavin]], he made a strong contribution with  by scoring three goals including a double against [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]]. However, his impact did little as they failed to qualify for the playoffs behind Portugal and [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]].\n\nUnder [[Guus Hiddink]], Kerzhakov continued his role as the first choice striker but was dropped after limited appearances for [[Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit]] in late 2006. Upon moving to Spain, Hiddink overlooked Kerzhakov for a friendly against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in February 2007, but recalled him a month later to face [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] following impressive performances for [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]. Kerzhakov went on to score both goals in the 2\u20130 victory over Estonia. In June 2007, Kerzhakov scored a hat-trick in a 4\u20130 victory over [[Andorra national football team|Andorra]]. He made a further contribution to Russia's [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualification|Euro 2008 qualification]] campaign by scoring a goal in a 3\u20130 victory over [[Macedonia national football team|Macedonia]] on September 2007. Despite being the top scorer for Russia with five goals, Kerzhakov was not included in Hiddink's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2008|the tournament finals]]. His poor form at Sevilla and less than impressive season at Dynamo Moscow led to a period of exclusion from the national team that lasted nearly 18 months.\n\nKerzhakov was finally recalled in May 2009 for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification - UEFA Group 4|2010 FIFA World Cup Qualifier]] against [[Finland national football team|Finland]] in Helsinki.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://football.uk.reuters.com/european/news/LQ943422.php |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121211220253/http://football.uk.reuters.com/european/news/LQ943422.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 December 2012 |title=Hiddink recalls Kerzhakov for Finland qualifier |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=26 May 2009 |publisher=Reuters UK }}</ref> He started the game and celebrated his return by scoring two goals as Russia defeated Finland 3\u20130. Kerzhakov was reinstated as the first choice striker and made a further four appearances in the qualifiers, helping his team finish behind Germany with 24 points. During the playoff against Slovenia, Kerzhakov was on the bench for first leg but was introduced at half-time for [[Roman Pavlyuchenko]] in the return fixture. In the 66th minute he received a straight red card after what was interpreted by referee [[Terje Hauge]] to be a deliberate kick at [[Slovenia]]n [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Samir Handanovi\u0107]]. Slovenia managed to hold on to a 1\u20130 win and Russia were eliminated on [[away goals rule|away goals]] after an aggregate 2\u20132 draw.\n\n===2010\u20132015: Record goalscorer===\n[[File:Trenirovka sbornoy (2).jpg|thumb|left|Kerzhakov training for Russia on 3 September 2014, ahead of the game when he broke the record for most goals for Russia]]\nKerzhakov's red card against earned him a suspension for two matches causing him to miss the first two qualifiers of the [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying|Euro 2012]] campaign. Upon being recalled by [[Dick Advocaat]], Kerzhakov scored in the victories over Ireland and Macedonia. Kerzhakov failed to score but managed to make three additional appearances as Russia topped [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying Group B|Group B]] to qualify directly for the final tournament. He was confirmed for the final [[UEFA Euro 2012]] squad, but the tournament turned into a major disappointment, as he scored no goals and Russia were eliminated in the first round.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://rfs.ru/main/news/ct131/73916.html| language = Russian | title = Advocaat announced the finalized Euro Squad|date=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Euro 2012 disappointment, former [[England national football team|England]] manager [[Fabio Capello]] was appointed and Kerzhakov was made the undisputed first choice striker after Andrei Arshavin, Roman Pavlyuchenko, and [[Pavel Pogrebnyak]] were dropped. Kerzhakov was Russia's top goalscorer during their [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualification campaign]] with five goals, including the winning goal in a 1\u20130 defeat of [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player=186808/profile-detail.html|title=Aleksandr KERZHAKOV|accessdate=18 June 2014|work=FIFA}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 June 2014, he was included in  Russia's [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Russian Football Union]]|url=http://rfs.ru/main/news/79322.html|script-title=ru:\u0421\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0427\u041c-2014|date=2 June 2014|language=Russian}}</ref> In the team's first match of the tournament, a 1\u20131 draw with [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]], Kerzhakov appeared as a 71st-minute substitute for [[Yuri Zhirkov]] and scored the team's equalising goal three minutes later. The goal was his 26th for Russia, equaling [[Vladimir Beschastnykh]]'s record for the national team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285141|title=Russia 1-1 South Korea|date=18 June 2014|accessdate=18 June 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> On 3 September 2014, in a 4&ndash;0 friendly win over [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]], he scored two goals and thus became the outright top scorer for the Russian national team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kerzhakov breaks record as Russia thrash Azerbaijan in friendly|url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/alexander-kerzhakov-breaks-record-as-russia-thrash-azerbaijan-in-friendly-090314|accessdate=3 September 2014|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Fox Sports|date=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nOn 15 March 2018, the [[Russian Football Union]] announced signing a contract with Kerzhakov to manage the [[Russia national under-17 football team]] until the end of 2019.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Russian Football Union]]|url=https://rfs.ru/news/206184|script-title=ru:\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041a\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b \u044e\u043d\u043e\u0448\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0443\u044e \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|date=15 March 2018|language=Russian}}</ref> The team became [[Russia national under-18 football team]] in September 2018 as the players aged.\n\n==Personal life==\nHis younger brother, [[Mikhail Kerzhakov|Mikhail]], is a professional footballer who also plays for Zenit St Petersburg as a goalkeeper.\n\nIn 2002, Kerzhakov authored his autobiography titled ''Up to 16 and older''. ({{lang-ru|\u0414\u043e 16 \u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0448\u0435}})\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/alexander-kerzhakov/5187/|title=Kerzhakov |publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=3 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"