{"title_page": "Ren Harvieu", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Ren Harvieu\n| image               = Ren Harvieu.jpg\n| landscape           = \n| alt                 = Harvieu performing at Manchester Pride, 25 August 2013\n| caption             = Harvieu performing at [[Manchester Pride]], 25 August 2013\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Lauren Maria Harvieu\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|9|3}} \n| birth_place         = [[Broughton, Salford]], England\n| origin              = \n| genre               = [[Pop rock]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[indie pop]]\n| occupation          = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 2011\u2013present\n| label               = [[Universal Music Group]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Lauren Maria''' \"'''Ren'''\" '''Harvieu''' (born 3 September 1990) is an English singer and songwriter from [[Broughton, Salford|Broughton]], [[City of Salford|Salford]], [[Greater Manchester]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nHarvieu was introduced to music by her mother. While in sixth form college, she performed in musical theatre and entered several talent competitions before uploading some of her own recordings to MySpace.<ref name=\"allmusic_bio\">{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ren-harvieu-mn0002848197 |title=Ren Harvieu \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography |first=Matt |last=Collar |work=[[AllMusic]] |year=2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRen Harvieu was discovered on [[MySpace]] by a local music manager after uploading demo tracks. After being introduced to record producer Jimmy Hogarth (Amy Winehouse, Duffy)  Ren began working on demo's and was signed to Universal Music aged 18.\n\nHarvieu started recording an album in May 2011, but before it could be released, she broke her back in what she describes as a 'freak accident', \"I heard it snap. I couldn't feel my feet,\" the singer recalled. After a 14-hour operation, Harvieu spent months recovering at the [[Royal National Orthopaedic Hospital]].<ref>Doyle, Tom. ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'', March 2012, #308. Q Now. The Singer Who Cheated Death. p. 35</ref>\n\nOn 5 December 2011, the BBC announced that she had been nominated for their BBC Sound of 2012 poll.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/soundof/2012/artists/renharvieu/#p00m9npy |title=BBC Sound of 2012: Ren Harvieu |work=bbc.co.uk |year=2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> After releasing the singles \"Through the Night\" and \"Open Up Your Arms\",<ref>{{cite web |url= https://itunes.apple.com/gb/artist/ren-harvieu/id485436005 |title=Ren Harvieu |work=[[iTunes]] |year=2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> her first album ''[[Through the Night (album)|Through the Night]]'' was released on Island Records on 14 May 2012, entering the UK album chart at No 5.\n\nIn 2014, Ren Harvieu was featured on \"Sweet Malaise\", the b-side to \"In My Time of Dust\", from [[Ed Harcourt]]'s mini-album ''[[Time of Dust]]''.<ref>http://www.qthemusic.com/1944/listen-ed-harcourts-sweet-malaise-featuring-ren-harvieu/</ref> \"Love is a Melody\", a song written by Ed Harcourt and Jimmy Hogarth for Harvieu's debut album, was also covered on ''Time of Dust''.<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/album/time-of-dust-mw0002607515</ref>\n\nHarvieu began working on her second album in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music/singer-rens-new-sound-feels-6064563 |title=Singer Ren's new sound feels so right |first=Dianne |last=Bourne |work=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date=19 September 2013 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> The album, titled ''Revel in the Drama'', was released in April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/ren-harvieu-revel-in-the-drama-album-review/|title=Ren Harvieu Invites You To 'Revel In The Drama' With Her Sumptuous, Opulent Opus|work=[[American Songriter]]|last=Horowitz|first=Hal|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! <small>[[UK Albums Chart|UK]]</small>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Through the Night (album)|Through the Night]]''\n|\n* Released: 14 May 2012\n* Label: [[Island Records|Island]]\n* Formats: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 5\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Revel in the Drama''\n|\n* Released: 3 April 2020\n* Label: [[Bella Union]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! <small>[[UK Albums Chart|UK]]</small>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Through the Night\"\n| 2011\n| 178\n|rowspan=\"4\"| ''Through the Night''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Open Up Your Arms\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2012\n| 108\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Tonight\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Do Right By Me\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Teenage Mascara\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n| \u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"| ''Revel in the Drama''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Yes Please\"\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  style=\"text-align:center; width:35px;\"|Year\n!Artist\n!Track\n!Album\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2013\n|[[Mark Owen]]\n|\"S.A.D.\"\n|''[[The Art of Doing Nothing]]''\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Organisation\n! Award\n! Result\n!\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[BBC]]\n| [[Sound of...|Sound of 2012]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.renharvieu.co.uk}}{{dead link|date=July 2015}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harvieu, Ren}}\n[[Category:English singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:People from Broughton, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Ren Harvieu\n| image               = Ren Harvieu.jpg\n| landscape           = \n| alt                 = Harvieu performing at Manchester Pride, 25 August 2013\n| caption             = Harvieu performing at [[Manchester Pride]], 25 August 2013\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Lauren Maria Harvieu\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|9|3}} \n| birth_place         = [[Broughton, Salford]], England\n| origin              = \n| genre               = [[Pop rock]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[indie pop]]\n| occupation          = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 2011\u2013present\n| label               = [[Universal Music Group]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Lauren Maria''' \"'''Ren'''\" '''Harvieu''' (born 3 September 1990) is an English singer and songwriter from [[Broughton, Salford|Broughton]], [[City of Salford|Salford]], [[Greater Manchester]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nHarvieu was introduced to music by her mother. While in sixth form college, she performed in musical theatre and entered several talent competitions before uploading some of her own recordings to MySpace.<ref name=\"allmusic_bio\">{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ren-harvieu-mn0002848197 |title=Ren Harvieu \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography |first=Matt |last=Collar |work=[[AllMusic]] |year=2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRen Harvieu was discovered on [[MySpace]] by a local music manager after uploading demo tracks. After being introduced to record producer Jimmy Hogarth (Amy Winehouse, Duffy)  Ren began working on demo's and was signed to Universal Music aged 18.\n\nHarvieu started recording an album in May 2011, but before it could be released, she broke her back in what she describes as a 'freak accident', \"I heard it snap. I couldn't feel my feet,\" the singer recalled. After a 14-hour operation, Harvieu spent months recovering at the [[Royal National Orthopaedic Hospital]].<ref>Doyle, Tom. ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'', March 2012, #308. Q Now. The Singer Who Cheated Death. p. 35</ref>\n\nOn 5 December 2011, the BBC announced that she had been nominated for their BBC Sound of 2012 poll.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/soundof/2012/artists/renharvieu/#p00m9npy |title=BBC Sound of 2012: Ren Harvieu |work=bbc.co.uk |year=2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> After releasing the singles \"Through the Night\" and \"Open Up Your Arms\",<ref>{{cite web |url= https://itunes.apple.com/gb/artist/ren-harvieu/id485436005 |title=Ren Harvieu |work=[[iTunes]] |year=2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> her first album ''[[Through the Night (album)|Through the Night]]'' was released on Island Records on 14 May 2012, entering the UK album chart at No 5.\n\nIn 2014, Ren Harvieu was featured on \"Sweet Malaise\", the b-side to \"In My Time of Dust\", from [[Ed Harcourt]]'s mini-album ''[[Time of Dust]]''.<ref>http://www.qthemusic.com/1944/listen-ed-harcourts-sweet-malaise-featuring-ren-harvieu/</ref> \"Love is a Melody\", a song written by Ed Harcourt and Jimmy Hogarth for Harvieu's debut album, was also covered on ''Time of Dust''.<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/album/time-of-dust-mw0002607515</ref>\n\nHarvieu began working on her second album in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music/singer-rens-new-sound-feels-6064563 |title=Singer Ren's new sound feels so right |first=Dianne |last=Bourne |work=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date=19 September 2013 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> The album, titled ''Revel in the Drama'', was released in April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/ren-harvieu-revel-in-the-drama-album-review/|title=Ren Harvieu Invites You To 'Revel In The Drama' With Her Sumptuous, Opulent Opus|work=[[American Songriter]]|last=Horowitz|first=Hal|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! <small>[[UK Albums Chart|UK]]</small>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Through the Night (album)|Through the Night]]''\n|\n* Released: 14 May 2012\n* Label: [[Island Records|Island]]\n* Formats: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 5\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Revel in the Drama''\n|\n* Scheduled: 3 April 2020\n* Label: [[Bella Union]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! <small>[[UK Albums Chart|UK]]</small>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Through the Night\"\n| 2011\n| 178\n|rowspan=\"4\"| ''Through the Night''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Open Up Your Arms\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2012\n| 108\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Tonight\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Do Right By Me\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Teenage Mascara\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n| \u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"| ''Revel in the Drama''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Yes Please\"\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  style=\"text-align:center; width:35px;\"|Year\n!Artist\n!Track\n!Album\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2013\n|[[Mark Owen]]\n|\"S.A.D.\"\n|''[[The Art of Doing Nothing]]''\n|}\n\n==Awards and nomin