{"title_page": "Haakon, Crown Prince of Norway", "text_new": "{{update|date=December 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2008}}\n{{stack|{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Haakon\n| title = Crown Prince of Norway\n| image = Crown Prince Haakon of Norway 2012-03-26 001.jpg\n| caption = The Crown Prince in 2012\n| succession =\n| reign =\n| cor-type = Benediction\n| coronation = \n| predecessor = \n| suc-type =\n| successor =\n| reg-type =\n| regent =\n| full name = Haakon Magnus\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|df=y|1973|7|20}}\n| birth_place  = [[Oslo University Hospital, Rikshospitalet|The National Hospital]], [[Oslo]], Norway\n| death_place  = \n| burial_date  = \n| burial_place = \n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Mette-Marit Tjessem H\u00f8iby]]|25 August 2001}}\n| issue = {{plain list|\n* [[Princess Ingrid Alexandra]]\n* [[Prince Sverre Magnus]]\n}}\n| house = [[House of Gl\u00fccksburg|Gl\u00fccksburg]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Royal Family|url=http://www.royalcourt.no/seksjon.html?tid=28435&sek=27259|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref>\n| father = [[Harald V of Norway]]\n| mother = [[Queen Sonja of Norway|Sonja Haraldsen]]\n| signature =\n}}\n{{Norwegian Royal Family}}\n}}\n\n'''Haakon, Crown Prince of Norway''' ({{IPA-no|\u02c8h\u00f2\u02d0k\u028an}}; Haakon Magnus; born 20 July 1973) is the only son of [[Harald V of Norway|King Harald V]] and [[Queen Sonja of Norway|Queen Sonja]], and [[heir apparent]] to the [[throne of Norway]].\n\nIn 2001, Haakon married [[Mette-Marit Tjessem H\u00f8iby]] with whom he has two children. He has an older sister, [[Princess M\u00e4rtha Louise of Norway|Princess M\u00e4rtha Louise]]. In accordance with Norway's [[agnatic primogeniture]] succession, Haakon became crown prince when his father ascended the throne on 17 January 1991 upon the death of his grandfather [[Olav V of Norway|Olav V]].\n\nThe [[Skaugum|Skaugum Estate]], situated in the area of [[Semsvannet]], is the official residence of the Crown Prince and Crown Princess.<ref>[http://www.royalcourt.no/artikkel.html?tid=28708&sek=28594 The Royal House of Norway - Skaugum Estate]</ref>\n\n== Family and early life ==\nHaakon was born in 20 July 1973 at [[Oslo University Hospital, Rikshospitalet|The National Hospital]] in [[St. Hanshaugen]], [[Oslo]], the only son and younger child of [[Harald V of Norway|Crown Prince Harald]] and [[Queen Sonja of Norway|Crown Princess Sonja]]. His father was the son of the reigning Norwegian monarch, [[Olav V of Norway|King Olav V]]. At birth he was named Haakon Magnus, and it was stressed in the announcement that he would go by the name Haakon.{{refn|His godparents are King [[Olav V of Norway]], [[Princess Astrid of Norway]], [[Prince Carl, Duke of \u00d6sterg\u00f6tland|Prince Carl Bernadotte]], King [[Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden]], Queen [[Margrethe II of Denmark]], and [[Anne, Princess Royal|Anne, Princess Royal of the United Kingdom]].{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}}} He was named in honor of his paternal great-grandfather, [[Haakon VII of Norway|King Haakon VII]], and his maternal uncle Haakon Haraldsen. When Haakon was only 17, his grandfather Olav died on 17 January 1991, leading to the ascension of his father as King Harald V and himself as crown prince.\n\nHaakon has one sibling, [[Princess M\u00e4rtha Louise of Norway]] (born 1971). In 1990, the Norwegian constitution was altered, granting [[primogeniture#Absolute primogeniture|absolute primogeniture]] to the Norwegian throne, meaning that the eldest child, regardless of gender, takes precedence in the line of succession. This was not, however, done retroactively (as, for example, Sweden had done in 1980), meaning that Haakon continues to take precedence over his older sister. He is also in the [[line of succession to the British throne]], albeit highly removed, as a great-great-grandson of [[Edward VII]].\n\n=== Education and military ===\nHaakon has served in the [[Royal Norwegian Navy]], where he undertook his first-level officer's education at the [[Norwegian Naval Academy]]. This was then followed with a year aboard missile [[torpedo boat]]s and other vessels. He received a Bachelor of Arts degree in [[political science]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Crown-Prince-Breaks-Tradition-at-Berkeley-2969170.php|title=Crown Prince Breaks Tradition at Berkeley / Norway's royal son has enrolled at Cal|work=SFGate|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref> Haakon later attended lectures at the [[University of Oslo]] and took the Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs' civil servant introductory course in 2001. He completed his education in 2003 at the [[London School of Economics]], where he was awarded an MSc in development studies, specializing in international trade and Africa.\n\nAs of 15 November 2013, in the Royal Norwegian Navy his [[officer rank]] is [[Military ranks and insignia of Norway|Admiral]], and in the [[Norwegian Army]] and the [[Royal Norwegian Air Force]] his rank is [[General]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regjeringen.no/nb/aktuelt/hans-kongelige-hoyhet-kronprinsen-utnevn/id745632/ |title=Hans Kongelige H\u00f8yhet Kronprinsen utnevnes til admiral og general |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=15 November 2013 |website=[[Government.no]] |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Norway)|Ministry of Defence]] |accessdate=14 December 2013 |language=Norwegian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613184317/https://www.regjeringen.no/nb/aktuelt/hans-kongelige-hoyhet-kronprinsen-utnevn/id745632/ |archivedate=13 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== Marriage and children ==\n{{See also|Wedding of Haakon, Crown Prince of Norway, and Mette-Marit Tjessem H\u00f8iby}}\n\nHaakon married a [[commoner]] and single mother [[Mette-Marit Tjessem H\u00f8iby]] on 25 August 2001, at [[Oslo Cathedral]]. [[Frederik, Crown Prince of Denmark]] was the [[best man]]. When the engagement between Crown Prince Haakon and H\u00f8iby was announced, many [[Norwegians]] felt that his choice of wife was inappropriate.<ref name=\"Hello\">[http://www.hellomagazine.com/profiles/crown-princess-mette-marit/ ''Hello'' profile of the Crown Princess]{{better source|date=June 2016}}</ref> This was primarily about her being a single mother, but information concerning her involvement in the [[rave]] scene in Oslo, which included a significant drug-subculture, also added to the controversy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Crown-Prince-Haakon-and-Crown-Princess-Mette-Marit|title=Crown Prince, and Crown Princess Mette-Marit Haakon|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref> In addition, the father of her child was convicted of drug-related offences.<ref name=\"Hello\" /> In a heartfelt press conference before the wedding the bride explained her past, saying among other things that her youthful rebelliousness might have been stronger than most young people.<ref name=\"Hello\" /> The issue of Mette-Marit's past is an ongoing discussion in Norwegian public discourse.\n\nThe couple have two children together: [[Princess Ingrid Alexandra of Norway]] (born 21 January 2004 at Oslo University National Hospital in Oslo) and [[Prince Sverre Magnus]] (born 3 December 2005 in Oslo University National Hospital in Oslo). Haakon is also the stepfather to Mette-Marit's son Marius Borg H\u00f8iby.\n\n== Activities ==\n[[File:16-11-2015 Presidente em exerc\u00edcio, Michel Temer, recebe no Itamaraty o pr\u00edncipe herdeiro da Noruega, Haakon Magnus (23069823405).jpg|thumb|Haakon with then-Brazilian Vice President [[Michel Temer]] at the [[Itamaraty Palace]] in [[Bras\u00edlia]], Brazil, 16 November 2015.]]\n\nFrom 25 November 2003 to 12 April 2004, Haakon was [[regent]] during the King's treatment for cancer and the subsequent convalescence period. Likewise, Haakon was Regent from 29 March 2005 until the King had fully recovered from the heart surgery he underwent on 1 April. This period ended on 7 June.\n\nIn addition to his official duties, Haakon has a strong interest in cultural matters. He also has given patronage to a number of organisations. In 2006, Haakon established [[Global Dignity]] with [[Pekka Himanen]] and [[John Hope Bryant]]. Global Dignity is an independent, non-political organization that promotes the universal right of every human being to lead a dignified life. Members of the organization include entrepreneurs [[Sir Richard Branson]] and [[Sandro Salsano]].\n\n=== Personal interests ===\nHaakon was involved in several sports and seemed to take a particular liking to [[windsurfing]] and surfing. However, he has not engaged in serious competitions. Haakon is known as a big music fan. When he was younger, he attended music festivals all over Europe, including the [[Roskilde Festival]] in Denmark and the [[Quart Festival]] in [[Kristiansand]], Norway.\n\nHe has also been part of Olympics ceremonies. In 1994, the Crown Prince and his father played roles during the opening ceremony in [[1994 Winter Olympics|Lillehammer]]. While the King declared open the Games, the Crown Prince [[List of people who have lit the Olympic Cauldron|lit the cauldron]], paying tribute to his father and grandfather having served as Olympians. He attended the [[2010 Winter Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony of the 2010 Winter Olympics]] in Vancouver.\n\nHe accompanied the band [[Katzenjammer (band)|Katzenjammer]] in their recording of the song \"Vi tenner v\u00e5re lykter\" (for the 2011 [[Christmas]]-themed album of the same name). Proceeds benefited \"Their Royal Highnesses The Crown Prince and Crown Princess funds.\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ToFpo4KAz0s&feature=autoplay&list=ALHTd1VmZQRNqTchQ9d7Y-IbEf7L_wptrN&playnext=12 Katzenjammer - Vi tenner v\u00e5re lykter], accessed October 26, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles, honours and awards==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Coat of Arms of His Royal Highness the Crown Prince of Norway.svg|[[Coat of arms of Norway|Coat of arms\nFile:Royal Monogram of Prince Haakon of Norway.svg|Monogram\n</gallery>\n===Titles===\n* 20 July 1973 - 17 January 1991: His Royal Highness Prince Haakon of Norway\n* 17 January 1991 \u2013 present: His Royal Highness The Crown Prince of Norway\n\n===Honours===\n{{see also|List of honours of the Norwegian Royal Family by country}}\n\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}} (\u00b0 = Honours mentioned on his official website [http://www.kongehuset.no/c34892/artikkel/vis.html?tid=34905 page])\n\n<center>\n[[File:St Olavs Orden storkors stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n[[File:Den kongelige norske fortjenstorden storkors stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n[[File:Forsvarsmedaljen med laurb\u00e6rgren stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n\n[[File:Kongehusets 100-\u00e5rsmedalje stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n[[File:Olav Vs minnemedalje stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n[[File:Olav Vs jubileumsmedalje 1957-1982 stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n\n[[File:Olav Vs 100-\u00e5rsmedalje stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n[[File:Kong Harald Vs jubileumsmedalje 1991-2016.png|100x30px]]\n[[File:Vernedyktighetsmedaljen Sj\u00f8forsvaret med 1 stjerne.svg|100x30px]]\n\n[[File:Norske reserveoffiserers forbunds hederstegn stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n[[File:Sj\u00f8milit\u00e6re Samfunds fortjenstmedalje stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n[[File:Oslo milit\u00e6re samfunds hederstegn stripe.svg|100x30px]]\n</center>\n\n====National honours====\n* Knight Grand Cross with Collar of the [[Order of St. Olav|Order of Saint Olav]] \u00b0\n* Knight Grand Cross of [[the Royal Norwegian Order of Merit|Order of Merit]] \u00b0\n* [[Defence Service Medal with Laurel Branch]] \u00b0\n* [[Royal House Centennial Medal]] \u00b0\n* [[Olav V's Commemorative Medal]] \u00b0\n* [[Olav V's Jubilee Medal]] \u00b0\n* [[Olav V's Centenary Medal]] \u00b0\n* [[King Harald V's Jubilee Medal 1991-2016]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Tildeling av Kong Harald Vs jubileumsmedalje 1991-2016|url=http://www.kongehuset.no/binfil/download2.php?tid=133159|website=Kongehuset|accessdate=20 January 2016|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n* [[National Service Medal|Royal Norwegian Navy Service Medal]] \u00b0\n* Norwegian Reserve Officers' Association Badge of Honour \u00b0\n* Naval Society Medal of Merit in gold \u00b0\n* Oslo Military Society Badge of Honour in Gold \u00b0\n\n====Foreign honours====\n* {{Flag|Austria}}: Grand Decoration in Gold with Sash of the [[Decoration of Honour for Services to the Republic of Austria|Order of Honour for Services to the Republic of Austria]]<ref name=\"AutHMM\">[http://typischich.at/home/leute/starnews/746708/Royals-Charity_Prinzessin-MetteMarit?gal=746708&index=5&direct=&_vl_backlink=&popup=#frame] - website typischich.at</ref><ref name=\"Aut1811\">{{cite web | url = http://www.parlament.gv.at/PAKT/VHG/XXIV/AB/AB_10542/imfname_251156.pdf | title = Reply to a parliamentary question about the Decoration of Honour | language = German | page=1811 |trans-title=| format = pdf | accessdate = November 2012 }}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Brazil}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Southern Cross]]\n* {{Flag|Bulgaria}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Stara Planina|Order of the Balkan Mountains]]\n* {{Flag|Denmark}}: Knight of [[Order of the Elephant]] \u00b0 (20 July 1991)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kongehuset.dk/modtagere-af-danske-dekorationer|title=Modtagere af danske dekorationer|date=2017-12-12|website=Kongehuset|language=da|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Estonia}}: Member 1st Class of [[Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]] \u00b0 (10 April 2002)<ref>Official website of the President of Estonia ''([[Estonian language|Estonian]])\n* Estonia: Member 1st Class of the ((Order of the White Star))\n [http://www.president.ee/en/estonia/decorations/bearers.php?id=367 Estonian State Decorations - Kroonprints Haakon]</ref>\n* {{Flag|Estonia}}: Member 1st Class of [[Order of the White Star]] (26 August 2014)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.president.ee/en/estonia/decorations/bearer/19149/haakon|title=Vabariigi President|website=www.president.ee|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Finland}}: Commander Grand Cross of the [[Order of the White Rose]] \u00b0<ref>[http://www.noblesseetroyautes.com/nr01/2012/10/diner-en-lhonneur-du-president-de-finlande-au-palais-royal-doslo/ Noblesse et Royaut\u00e9s] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317090625/http://www.noblesseetroyautes.com/nr01/2012/10/diner-en-lhonneur-du-president-de-finlande-au-palais-royal-doslo/ |date=17 March 2013 }} (French), State visit of President of Finland in Norway, 2012, [http://www.noblesseetroyautes.com/nr01/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/puku1_1010JID_vi.jpg Photo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317091441/http://www.noblesseetroyautes.com/nr01/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/puku1_1010JID_vi.jpg |date=17 March 2013 }}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Germany}}: Grand Cross 1st Class of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]] \u00b0\n* {{Flag|Iceland}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Falcon]].<ref>http://www.kongehuset.no/nyhet.html?tid=152550&sek=26939</ref>\n* {{Flag|Italy}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] (20 September 2004) \u00b0<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quirinale.it/onorificenze/insigniti/144229|title=Le onorificenze della Repubblica Italiana|website=www.quirinale.it|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Japan}}: Knight Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Chrysanthemum]]<ref>[http://www.kongehuset.no/c34892/artikkel/vis.html?tid=34905 Norwegian Crown Prince website]</ref>\n* {{Flag|Jordan}}: Knight Grand Cordon of the [[Supreme Order of the Renaissance]]\n* {{Flag|Latvia}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Three Stars]] (20 September 2000) \u00b0<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vestnesis.lv/ta/id/11126|title=Par Norv\u0113\u0123ijas Karalistes pavalstnieku apbalvo\u0161anu\u2026 - Latvijas V\u0113stnesis|last=vestnesis.lv|website=www.vestnesis.lv|language=lv|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Latvia}}: Grand Cross of the [[Cross of Recognition|Order of Recognition]]\n* {{Flag|Lithuania}} : Grand Cross of the [[Order of Vytautas the Great]] (23 March 2011)<ref>[http://www.lrp.lt/lt/prezidento_veikla/apdovanojimai/apdovanojimai_256/p40.html Lithuanian Presidency] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419212238/http://www.lrp.lt/lt/prezidento_veikla/apdovanojimai/apdovanojimai_256/p40.html |date=19 April 2014 }}, Lithuanian Orders searching form</ref><ref>[http://theroyalcorrespondent.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/1302033364000_20110405-_4_3718912698x698r.jpg Photo] of a State visit of Lithuania to Norway, March 2011</ref> \u00b0\n* {{Flag|Luxembourg}}: Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of Adolph of Nassau]] \u00b0\n* {{Flag|Netherlands}}: Knight Grand Cross with Swords of the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]] \u00b0\n* {{Flag|Poland}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]] (16 September 2003)\u00b0<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://prawo.sejm.gov.pl/isap.nsf/DocDetails.xsp?id=WMP20040020034|title=Postanowienie Prezydenta Rzeczypospolitej Polskiej z dnia 15 wrze\u015bnia 2003 r. o nadaniu order\u00f3w|website=prawo.sejm.gov.pl|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Portugal}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Prince Henry|Order of Infante Henry]] (13 February 2004) \u00b0<ref>[https://dre.pt/web/guest/pesquisa/-/search/3045513/details/normal Alvar\u00e1 n.\u00ba 2/2004]. Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica n.\u00ba 77/2004, S\u00e9rie II de 2004-03-3. p.5092.</ref>\n* {{Flag|Slovenia}}: Recipient of [[The Golden Order of Merit in the military or security fiel]] \u00b0 (6 November 2019)\n* {{Flag|Spain}}: Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of Charles III]] (26 May 2006)\u00b0<ref>[http://www.boe.es/boe/dias/2006/05/27/pdfs/A20010-20010.pdf Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado]</ref>\n* {{Flag|Sweden}}: Knight of the [[Royal Order of the Seraphim]] \u00b0\n\n===Awards===\n* 14 August Committee's Bridge Building Prize 2011<ref>[http://www.newsinenglish.no/2011/08/10/crown-prince-wins-pakistani-prize/ Crown Prince wins Pakistani prize] \u2013 website Views and News from Norway</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Olympic flag.svg}} Olympic Games : [[List of people who have lit the Olympic Cauldron|Lighter of the Olympic Cauldron]]; [[1994 Winter Olympics]] in [[Lillehammer]], opened by his father, [[Harald V of Norway|King Harald V]].\n* A horse race bears his name, [[Kronprins Haakons Pokall\u00f8p]].  It is held every year in June, at [[Drammen Travpark]].\n\n==Ancestry==\nHe is a third cousin of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], [[heir apparent]] of the United Kingdom. As a descendant of King [[Edward VII|Edward VII of the United Kingdom]], Haakon is also eligible to [[Line of succession to the British throne|succeed]] to the thrones of the sixteen [[Commonwealth realm]]s.\n{{Ahnentafel\n|align=center|collapsed=yes\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Haakon, Crown Prince of Norway'''\n|2= 2. [[Harald V of Norway]]\n|3= 3. [[Queen Sonja of Norway|Sonja Haraldsen]]\n|4= 4. [[Olav V of Norway]]\n|5= 5. [[Princess M\u00e4rtha of Sweden]]\n|6= 6. Karl August Haraldsen\n|7= 7. Dagny Ulrichsen\n|8= 8. [[Haakon VII of Norway]]\n|9= 9. [[Maud of Wales|Princess Maud of Wales]]\n|10= 10. [[Prince Carl, Duke of V\u00e4sterg\u00f6tland]]\n|11= 11. [[Princess Ingeborg of Denmark]]\n|12= 12. Halvor Haraldsen<ref name=\"National Archives of Norway\">{{cite web|title=National Archives of Norway|url=http://www.arkivverket.no/URN:kb_read?idx_kildeid=5996&uid=ny&idx_side=-52|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref>\n|13= 13. Karete Josefine Nielsdatter<ref name=\"National Archives of Norway\"/>\n|14= 14.  Johan Christian Ulrichsen<ref>{{cite web|title=National Archives of Norway-listed as Joh. C. Ulrichsen|url=http://digitalarkivet.arkivverket.no/ft/person/pf01036515002358|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"arkivverket.no\">{{cite web|title=National Archives of Norway|url=http://www.arkivverket.no/URN:kb_read?idx_kildeid=3556&idx_id=3556&uid=ny&idx_side=-252|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Image of Grave Site\">{{cite web|title=Image of Grave Site|url=http://image2.findagrave.com/photos/2007/230/21025970_118756366577.jpg|accessdate=21 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821174009/http://image2.findagrave.com/photos/2007/230/21025970_118756366577.jpg|archive-date=21 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|15= 15. Marie Berntine Hansen<ref name=\"arkivverket.no\"/><ref name=\"Image of Grave Site\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=National Archives of Norway-listed as Maja Ulrichsen|url=http://digitalarkivet.arkivverket.no/ft/person/pf01036515002358|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.royalcourt.no/artikkel.html?tid=28766&sek=28640 Haakon's biography on the Royal Court's official website]\n* [https://tv.nrk.no/serie/kongefamilien/FAKN70000091/20-07-1991 Haakon, Norges kronprins]. NRK interview for his 18th birthday\n* [http://www.vg.no/rampelys/artikkel.php?artid=10032263 (translation of title: - The couple, the Crown Prince and Crown Princess, are doing political work) \"- ''Kronprinsparet driver politisk arbeid''\" ]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Gl\u00fccksburg]]|20 July|1973|Living}}\n{{s-roy|no}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Harald V of Norway|Prince Harald]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Monarchy of Norway|Crown Prince of Norway]]|years=1991\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|heir=[[Princess Ingrid Alexandra of Norway|Princess Ingrid Alexandra]]}}\n{{S-other|line}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-non|reason=First in line}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Line of succession to the Norwegian throne]]|years=1st position}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Princess Ingrid Alexandra of Norway]]}}\n{{s-bef| before= [[Harald V of Norway|The King of Norway]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Line of succession to the British throne]] |creation = descended from [[Maud of Wales|Maud]], daughter o